Of the MSS. which I have been able to test a certain number are of the M-type, rather more are of the C-type, while the most numerous class shows a conflate text, the basis being of the C-type, but- contaminated by insertions and corrections of the M-type.

Apart from minuter (lifferences of reading, the more important points in which the two types differ are these.

1. The clause in Which Bede asks for the prayers of his readers, ‘Praeterea omnes . . . inueniam,’ p. 8, is found at the end of the Preface in the M-text, but in the C-text it is placed at the end of the work.

2. The chapter which is numbered iv. 14 in the editions is omitted altogether in MSS. of a pure C-type ¹.
